                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>546 N. 5th St.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Philadelphia&#44; July 8&#44; &#39;89.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev. Dr. B. Felsenthal.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>My Dear Sir &#38; Respected Friend&#58;<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Your very kind letter just received&#44; is<lb/> amply appreciated.  Accept my sincere thanks.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>The edition of &#91;Hebrew&#93; in my possession<lb/> is Venice 1595.  It is by no means free from errors.  Years<lb/> ago&#44; reading it with the pupils of the defunct Maimonides<lb/> College&#44; I detected in numerable omissions and blunders.  Pro&#45;<lb/>fessor Rosin&#39;s work&#44; to which Dr. Bellelheim refers&#44; I have<lb/> not seen.  If Dr. Jastrow were in town&#44; I might borrow it&#44; as<lb/> I fancy he has it.  The Dr. lent me Rosin&#39;s edition of &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/> containing some interesting prefatory remarks and clear anno&#45;<lb/>tations.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>I am not so certain that the author of<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93; intended to intimate the existence of a biennial<lb/> cycle.  I would term my inference &#40;<hi rend="underline">in point and apprise</hi>&#44;&#41; or<lb/> &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; even less than that&#44; and you should&#44; my<lb/> dear Sir&#44; represent it as such in having it brought before the<lb/> public.  I hold that the dignity of Hebrew literature demands<lb/> exceeding carefulness on our part not to jump at conclusions.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>I agree with you that the &#91;Hebrew&#93; is a stumb&#45;<lb/>ling block in the way of the &#91;Hebrew&#93;&#44; and the two cannot be re&#45;<lb/>conciled&#44; except &#91;Hebrew&#93;.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>To your question&#44; why I did not address<lb/> the <hi rend="underline">Menorah</hi> I answer&#44; that I considered that procedure formal<lb/> and unfriendly.  It was due to you&#44; that I should submit my<lb/> remarks to your judgment&#44; and leave it to your option to pub&#45;<lb/>lish them in full&#44; in part&#44; or enlarged upon my<sic></sic> your sensible<lb/> observations.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Like yourself&#44; I have reason to deplore<lb/> the want of fairness in our journals&#44; the abundance of buncombe<lb/> in some&#44; the fulsome flattery or cutting reflections in others.<lb/>  However&#44; thirty six years and a half have familiarized me with<lb/> all that&#44; and what pained or gladdened me in years past&#44; I read<lb/> now with tolerable composure.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Live happily and believe me&#44; yours with<lb/> high regard<lb/> S. Morais<lb/></p>
                
            <p>P. S.  I remember that you asked me once&#44; whether certain un&#45;<lb/>common Biblical names were used in Italy.  Since then I met<lb/> with some&#44; f.r. &#91;Hebrew&#93; Bianchini<lb/> Finzi &#91;Hebrew&#93; Finzi &#91;Hebrew&#93; De Lapapa<lb/> and similar&#44; scattered among various books&#44; especially of &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
            </body>
